animal.description: MEET MADISON EVA! This little bitty lady is as bubbly as they come! Madison is very sweet and loving, and she loves to play a combination of fetch and tug. Madison needs a patient person. She was not treated very well by her previous owners and can scare easily. Because of this, she does nervous pee during those times. She is good in her crate but would need some work with house training her. She is good in the house as far as not chewing on things but does have the occasional accident when left out on her own in the house. Madison can be nervous around dogs she doesn’t know and tends to be selective about the ones she likes but she has come a long way since we first rescued her. Even though she can tolerate others on leash and in passing, Madison needs to be the only pet in the home. She loves kids of all ages! :) To adopt or foster Madison please contact us at destiny@dogsofdestiny.com for more info or fill out an application at dogsofdestiny.com.

animal.description: Meet HUEY!! You may remember this cutie patootie. He was originally seized by animal control after his family, who had neglected and abused him, treating him so much like a lawn ornament, left him chained in the yard when they moved away. Huey has been doing just wonderfully here at rescue! He is one of our RADAR dogs and has been through his heartworm treatment thanks to them! Huey is also deaf. We've been working with him on not being so mouthy when he interacts with people, as well as trusting us that he won't be hurt when he comes to us. He has made such wonderful progress and actually now approaches you to be loved on and to get treats!! He has been doing very well with his dog interactions but in unknown with cats. We are so happy Huey is learning to "dog!” While we work with Huey on his mouthing, he is currently only available to foster (we will consider adoption to a family experienced and understanding of the work they will need to continue with him and/or a foster to adopt situation under the same pretense). If interested in adopting or fostering, please contact us at destiny@dogsofdestiny.com for more info or fill out an application at dogsofdestiny.com. Please also keep in mind that Huey is deaf, so working with him is a little different! A contractual agreement of working with our behavior consultant for a minimum of 5 visits will be required.

animal.description: Meet DUNCAN CHRISTOPHER!! This super sweet guy is around 6 years old. He is very mid mannered but still loves to have fun! His play energy is low but peppy, and he loves his snuggle time and his peanut butter kongs. Duncan has been through numerous tests to find out what the issue causing his excessive urination and drinking is, but we have not been able to determine a cause. He is healthy all-around though! Duncan will need someone understanding of him having accidents because of this condition, but he does very well in his crate and will use pee pads. Duncan walks very well on leash and has done very well with people of all ages and other dogs! He is unknown with cats. animal.description: Meet NIGEL HARRISON!! We rescued this cutie patootie when the rescue he was with decided he had been with them too long, and they were going to put him down. From what we were told, he was in foster and the same decision had been made. A volunteer group stepped up and found him an adopter. The adopter decided she didn't want him anymore (apparently you can't teach a mostly deaf dog sign language, and she was disappointed that he wasn't totally deaf). Once again he was at risk of being put down since his rescue didn't want him back. They were once again scheduling him for euthanization. The volunteer group that thought they had saved him once before sent us an urgent plea for his life...and we answered. Nigel is super sweet and is a very young 7 years old! Nigel is hard of hearing but not deaf, and he is learning sign language regardless and is very well behaved! He also has food allergies so must be kept away from chicken or beef. His skin is very sensitive, and in the summer, he may break out in a hot spot and needs to get baths with a shampoo that is good for his skin (something with neem or tea tree oil in it...or even with ketoconazole). He can be a bit mouthy when he plays or tries to get your attention, so older children are recommended. He does well in his crate and has done very well in the house especially considering he had lived a good portion of his life outside only. This guy loves his peanut butter and loves his kisses! Nigel is available to foster or adopt. He has done well with other dogs he has Interacted with here. If interested in adopting or fostering this super sweet, handsome guy please email us at destiny@dogsofdestiny.com or fill out an application via our website at dogsofdestiny.com.

animal.description: Meet CHLOE!!! There just aren't enough nice things to be able to describe this sweetheart of a gal! Chloe is very gentle when taking food and giving kisses. While she likes to romp around in the yard, she doesn't necessarily have any particular type of a game she likes to play, and she does check in with you for pets and praise while romping about. She can be very nervous/on guard when meeting or seeing people wearing hats, so it is best to ensure people she meets are not wearing them. She can also be reactive at the vet's office/strange places toward other dogs she doesn't know. This could be in part because Chloe was in and out of vet's offices and back and forth to specialists when we determined she had cancer. She had surgery to remove the cancer and has been cancer free for over a year now! Along with her regular check ups, she needs to be checked to ensure she is staying cancer free. She is a very sweet girl and she has a sassy "talking" side too, and she will bark at you to let you know you aren't moving fast enough to give her meals or her treats, so you've got to be on top of that stuff! :) CHLOE wasn't very socially appropriate with other dogs while she was at the shelter. While at the shelter, she would do okay with other dogs until she became overly excited or overly stimulated and then would mount them. Once she did, she wouldn't really respond to any correction another dog would give her to let them know they didn't like being mounted. Since she has been here, she has been doing very well with her baby gate interactions and her on leash interactions. We have also seen a significant decline in her trying to mount the dogs she interacts with! She is doing very well! Chloe is very well behaved in the house when left alone and also does very well in a crate. She takes a little while to fully open up to you and show you her goofball side and her snuggly side, but once she does, the full spectrum of her sweetness really shines through! If interested in adopting or fostering, please contact us at destiny@dogsofdestiny.com for more info or fill out an application at dogsofdestiny.com.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Clint and I am a 3 year old Shepherd/Cattle dog mix. I am great with female humans but I seem not to like men. I am also very selective with other dogs. I would do best in a dominant breed experienced home and ideally, as an only dog. Ideally I would have female owners in a low activity home as I don’t care much for strangers. I must be in a home. Apartment living will not be considered for my adoption. 

I love my spa dates at P.A.W.S in Newhall, Love walks. Love being a roadie with my owners. Love getting pets and affection too! I have been dreaming about my own happy ever after. Hope that could be with you! 

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Interested in adopting? If so, please complete an adoption application first at www.delaneysdog.com/adoption-application.html

All Delaney's Dog adoption fees include :
-Up-to-date vaccinations
-Spay/neuter
-Microchip & microchip registration

The adoption process requires an initial approved Adoption Application, a home visit to ensure safety and well-being of adoptee & a separate Adoption Agreement.

**Adoption fees vary and are NOT NEGOTIABLE. 

NOTE: An Adoption Application does not guarantee an adoption. Adoptions are based on the best possible situation for each dog and their prospective owners. Not all breeds are right for all people and not all people are right for all breeds. Our commitment is to place these animals in the right homes so that they never again have to face re-homing. They deserve a forever family too.

Additionally, each adoption includes a one week, partial fee refundable, trial period to ensure pet is a right fit.

NO OUT OF STATE ADOPTIONS

animal.description:
Aisa was one of the many dogs we saved in Texas .

Also this pretty girl ended up on the kill list .

We were in time and she came save under our wings .

Many people ask us why these beautiful shepherds are getting killed.

Unfortunately, the mentality of the people where our dogs come from , they see dogs as an item that they can trow away as a piece of garbage .

Thousand and thousand of dogs are running on the streets . Litters, pregnant mommies , young dogs , old dogs , injured dogs . You can see it all. Animal control can not keep up and even when we are with 4 German shepherd rescues on that one shelter , we can not keep up.

Aisa was one of the lucky ones. When she went on our truck other ones were getting killed . The thin line between life and death .

Aisa is a wonderful sweet and calm 3 year old German Shepherd . We had no problems walking her on the leash . For now we would like to have her as pet only .

Aisa is looking for a nice family who will treat her like the rare gem she is .
A family who will love her and spoil her . Where she can forget her past .

Aisa is located in Middle ISland NY

To become her new family please apply today by filling in the  adoption application to find on our website www.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email is and we send you one .

animal.description:
Nikko needs a hero. He is once again a resident at HSBR because his adoption didn't work out. Because of the unsuccessful adoption, we have learned more about what Nikko needs to thrive and live a happy life.

Is Nikko a great dog? Yes he is! Will he make an awesome companion? Absolutely! He deserves the chance to shine and to be the wonderful dog he is. 

Nikko needs to be in a home with no children and no other pets. He is best suited to live with one adult because he is extremely loyal to and protective of his person. But with proper training and patience, he could very well adapt to living in a home with more than one adult. Although he functions well at HSBR when multiple staff members and/or volunteers tend to him, it appears he functions best with one person in a home environment.

Nikko prefers staying indoors, but when he goes outside, he needs to be in a fenced yard. He enjoys playing fetch, loves toys and is a big fan of car rides! 

If you are looking for a loyal canine who has so much love to give and will see you as the best thing since sliced bread, then Nikko is definitely for you. He is 3 years old, current on his vaccinations, neutered and microchipped. For more information about Nikko, contact HSBR at (706) 632-4357.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Online Adoption Application 
Gideon is a 7 year old cuddly boy in search of a good home. He is neutered and up to date on all vaccines, flea and heartworm preventative medication. He is great with children - lives with a 2 year old and a 3 year old and is incredibly patient with their attention. He loves attention and cuddles and regularly sits on people's laps if they are on the floor. He is housebroken. He is not currently crate trained but we are working on it.

Gideon is a protector with high anxiety. He goes on high alert when out with his people on walks or car rides. He has been on anxiety medication for 3 years and has some destructive habits when separated from his people. A good home for Gideon would require someone with the patience and knowledge to help him through his anxiety.

He needs a home with a yard, preferably fenced (high fence - he can jump!) so he can run and roam. He is prey driven and has caught rabbits, snakes and turtles (and tried to catch squirrels and birds). He does well with other dogs when properly introduced and attends doggy daycare occasionally. He was raised with another lab for the first few years of his life and LOVED her - I think he misses having a doggy friend but needs one that is not going to challenge his alpha spot or they may not get along. He has never been around a cat but I would worry about the prey drive in that situation. 2/2/21 4:05 PM

animal.description:
Mookie & Victory are a bonded pair

Video: https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=292784035174568 

Victory was only 10 weeks old in July 2019 when she was run over by a car and left on the side of the road. After two major initial surgeries, she went to the same foster home as Mookie. Even though he was only 5 months at the time, his gentleness and care for Victory melted our hearts. Victory had to undergo two additional surgeries. Mookie has been right by her side through all of her recoveries. They have a sweetness for each other that we just can’t separate, and we are adoptiong these two precious puppies as a bonded pair, together. Mookie is a total cuddler and loves to sleep next to his people in bed. He will curl up by you on the couch after a busy day of playing ball and chewing on his bones. He’s a confident, active, energetic pup with the most soulful puppy eyes you ever did see. Victory is also a love bug, with plenty of kisses to give. She’s a sweet, happy girl who wants to please her people. She's a complete darling, and everyone seems to just fall in love with her. Victory has been diagnosed with fibrotic myopathy which is a rare, idiopathic disorder. We officially consider Mookie her emotional support animal! If you’re interested in opening your heart and home to this pair of wonderful pups, we’ll be happy to talk to you further about Victory’s special needs.

Website:      http://www.goodshepherdrescuetexas.com/
Facebook:   https://www.facebook.com/GoodShepherdRescue
Application:  https://www.goodshepherdrescuetexas.com/adoption-application

PLEASE NOTE:  We do not respond to Petfinder inquiries with any information about the dogs.  Only pre-approved adopters are setup for meet & greets.  You must submit an application to start the approval process.  A volunteer will be in touch with you to discuss.  ALL dogs in our program are spayed / neutered, fully vaccinated, dewormed, microchipped, tested for heartworms & treated for heartworms if necessary.

Adoption Fees:
---------------------------------------------------------
400.00 - Purebred Puppy
350.00 - Purebred Adult
250.00 - Purebred Senior (7 and older)
300.00 - Mixed Breed Puppy
250.00 - Mixed Breed Adult

Please Note: WE ARE NOT A SHELTER- ALL DANES ARE IN FOSTER HOMES

Meet DELILAH! This sweet girl is about 15-24 months old She is partially deaf and has some vision impaired, but that doesn't slow her down. Delilah gets along with other dogs once she has been introduced to them properly. Delilah also does well with kiddos, but the kiddos have to be dog savvy and GDRST recommends children 10 or older.  Delilah also chases cats and a home with no cats is a must. Delilah loves to dress up and loves being in the water. Delilah does want to please her humans and has been out on several social occasions and did very well. Delilah needs a home that can allow her to run off her energy so she can wear herself out.  An active family would be perfect for Delilah. 

Delilah will need a home that knows, or is willing to learn, how to communicate with Delilah and the disability that she has. 

ADOPTION CONTRIBUTION FEE: $217.00 

In many cases, the cost of vetting services is greater than the adoption contribution. The adoption contributions help defray the costs of vetting services, but rarely, if ever, cover all expenses.   Additional donations are welcomed and appreciated. Please consider making a donation to help offset medical expenses.
To  do so, please  visit our website at www.saveadane.org

GDRST will have the following services completed as part of the adoption process. Each animal will be spayed or neutered, fully vaccinated, heartworm tested, heartworm treated if applicable, fecal tested, de-wormed, microchipped, and administered Heartgard.

Please note GDRST  is an all-volunteer, run by individuals with full-time careers. In order to meet with a Dane that you are interested in, you will need to complete an application. After receiving your application, a volunteer will verify with your vet the care on your current or previous animals. Then, we will contact you to set up a home visit and to discuss which Dane may be a match for you.

Houston, TX 77062-5723

animal.description:
JUDGE THEM NOT BY THE CUT OF THEIR COAT, BUT BY THE CONTENT OF THEIR CHARACTER!

***

CSAA ~ The CANINE SYNDICATE of ANIMAL ALLIANCE

The CSAA, most commonly know as "The Syndicate", is an underground organization formed in 2014 by "The Lifers".  Lifers are dogs who have spent the majority of their lives, if not their entire lives, without a proper home and have remained so even after rescue, spending two or more years waiting to be adopted.

The STRUCTURE

The core operatives of the organization are five, it's a hierarchical structure based on seniority.  There are four dogs and one cat.

OVERDOG ~ This is the highest level, top dog.  This position is occupied by the dog who has been in the network the longest.

UNDERDOG ~ This is the second-highest position, this dog is second in command and right-hand to the OVERDOG, this position is occupied by the dog who has been in the network second-longest.

CONSIGLIERE ~ This is the advisor or counselor to the OVERDOG. This position is occupied by the dog who has been in the network third-longest. 

RING BOSS ~  This is the overseer of the RING LEADERS.  This position is occupied by the dog who has been in the network forth-longest.

EMISSARY ~ This is the only top-level position held by a cat.  The Emissary acts as a diplomat and liaison between the Canine Syndicate, and it's antimatter equivalent, the Feline Syndicate.  This position is held by the cat who has been in the network the longest, outside of the core operatives of the Feline Syndicate.

The remaining dogs in the network who have been waiting for adoption two or more years are RING LEADERS.  They lead small crews with varying numbers of AGENTS, dogs who have been in the network for less than two years.

RING LEADERS are in line for top-level positions as they become vacant when senior members retire via adoption.

***

PROJECTS

Operation "Royal Flush" ~ Initiated August 10th, 2019

The objective of Operation Royal Flush was to retire all 5 founding core Syndicate operatives no later than 1/1/2020 via adoption. 

The project concluded on 1/1/2020, three out of five core operatives had been adopted, only Smiling Timmie and Slick Rick remained.

HISTORY of ADOPTIONS

1/20/2019 ~Baby Faced FITZ was adopted and has stepped down from his position as Underdog, the vacancy created was filled by the promotion of is mother, Four Stix FARRAH.

12/4/2019 ~ Four on the Floor LUCKY was adopted and has stepped down from his position as Underdog, the vacancy created was filled by the promotion of Baby Faced FITZ.

11/10/2019 ~ Little MARTHA was adopted and has stepped down from her position as Overdog, the vacancy created was filled by the promotion of Smiling TIMMIE.

9/19/2019 ~ Fast LEO was adopted and has stepped down from his position as Underdog, the vacancy created was filled by the promotion of Smiling TIMMIE.

8/21/2019 ~ Big Daddy MAKO was adopted and stepped down from his position as Underdog, the vacancy created was filled by the promotion of Fast LEO.

CURRENT PERSONNEL

1/20/2020 - Present

* Smiling TIMMIE ~ Overdog ~ 7/16/2014 (6 years)
* 4 Stix FARRAH ~ Underdog ~ 7/31/2016 (4 years)
* PEARL  ~ Consigliere ~ 9/15/2015 (5 years)
* BAXTER & BONNIE  ~ Ring Boss & Assistant RB ~ 08/22/2016 (4 years)
* SLICK RICK ~ Emissary ~ 12/16/2017 (3 years)

FOUNDING MEMBERS - (2013 - 8/21/2019)

* Little MARTHA ~ Overdog ~  7/9/2013 (6 years)
* Big Daddy MAKO ~ Underdog ~ 7/16/2014 (5 years)
* Fast LEO ~ Consigliere ~ 9/27/2016 (5 years)
* Smiling TIMMIE ~ Ring Boss ~ 7/31/2016 (6 years)
* SLICK RICK ~ Emissary ~ 12/16/2017 (3 years)

***

***

INTERVIEW WITH SLICK RICK - 9/13/2019

The DAILY BISCUIT
AA Tabloid News

SPECIAL EDITION - An exclusive interview with Syndicate Emissary, Slick Rick.

Recently, BISCUIT Investigators were approached by Canine Syndicate Consigliere, Smiling Timmie and offered the rare opportunity to interview one of its operatives. "If we intend to achieve the objectives outlined in Operation Royal Flush by the established deadline of 1/1/2020, some bold moves are in order. We're prepared to grant an interview." ~ Smiling Timmie

The following transcript details that interview.

*** 9/12/2019 - Biscuit Investigator (BI) & Slick Rick (SR) ***

BI: Good morning Mr. Rick, thank you for taking the time to speak with us today.

SR: My pleasure.

BI: Mr. Rick, I'd like to talk to you about Operation Royal Flush. Let's start with your prospects, do you think you will be adopted, and thus able to step down from your position as Emissary by 1/1/2020?

SR: Please, call me Slick.

BI: Sure. So do you feel your prospects for adoption are good Slick?

SR: Absolutely.

BI: Why so?

SR: I'm an asset.

BI: Please explain.

SR: I bring a lot to the table.

BI: Could you expand on that Slick?

SR: Sure. To start, I'm a diplomat, very easy to get along with, a goodwill ambassador if you will. I'm skilled at negotiating and keeping the peace, that's why I'm the Emissary. It's not easy you know, acting as Liaison between the Canine and Feline Syndicates. We're talking about an age-old struggle, the conflict between cats and dogs. Before my Syndicate days though, I was a street hustler, tough, gritty, very resourceful... totally independent, I didn't need help from anyone. Not until the incident anyway.

BI: The incident?

SR: Yeah, that's what actually brought me here to the Animal Alliance Shelter in Lambertville, known as "HQ" within the organization. Anyway, I'd been banged up pretty good in a fight, first time I ever had my ass handed to me like that, that was one tough tomcat! I had a nasty head injury and an even nastier infection. Then I started slipping into delirium, didn't know which way was up. When I finally came to my senses, I realized I was in the mysterious and mythical "Rescue Network" that I'd always heard about. Until then, I didn't believe the thing even existed. Thought it was just the pipe dream of delusional street cats, coughing and shivering in dumpsters.

BI: Can you tell me more about the Rescue Network?

SR: Okay sure. First, I'll need to acquaint you with the "Animal People", we also call them the Guardians. The Guardians are members of the Human Race who protect animal life. The Rescue Network is only one of their many projects.

BI: Are rescue volunteers Guardians?

SR: Yes, as are the adopters.

BI: You inferred that the Animal People were involved in other projects.

SR: Yes, the Animal People have many other projects, but that's for another interview.

BI: What is the Canine Syndicate's connection with the Rescue Network?

SR: Now we're getting into the deep end of the pool. Our organization exists within the Rescue Network, specifically that of Animal Alliance. It began when Little Martha and Big Daddy Mako founded the organization in 2014 when it was beginning to look like they might never be adopted. Then Smiling Timmie and Fast Leo were made in 2016. I arrived at HQ in 2017, it was early 2019 when I was approached by the Syndicate and made Emissary. We all began to realize that there was a growing number of us accumulating within the Network. Clearly, this was not what had been intended by the Animal People. So we came up with a plan, Operation Royal Flush.

BI: Please, continue.

SR: Right. So, we had given ourselves, and those in the same boat, an identity; the Lifers. We were individuals who had remained in the Network for two or more years after rescue, waiting for adoption. The objective of Operation Royal Flush was very specific, to grease the revolving door, get the Lifers adopted and bring in new rescues. Our tactical strategy was to start at the top of the seniority hierarchy and work our way down. We wanted to retire the highest-level operatives of the Syndicate via adoption first, promote the Ring Leaders next in line, and continue turning over the top tier until there were no more Lifers in the Network.

BI: I'm beginning to understand now. The Canine Syndicate was formed by Lifers, and the objective of Operation Royal Flush is to eliminate the Lifers via adoption.

SR: Exactamundo!

BI: Slick, is there anything, in particular, you would like to leave our readers with before we wrap it up?

SR: Yes, the next time you look at the AA adoptable pets list on Petfinder, start on the last page. The individuals you'll see on the last few pages are the Lifers. Every last one of us brings something special to the table and we'd really like the opportunity to show that to you. Believe me when I tell you, there are some once-in-a-lifetime friends to be found on those pages!

BI: Slick, this has been a very informative and enjoyable conversation. Thank you for granting us this interview.

SR: You're very welcome.

animal.description:
The Keeshond foster dogs pictured here have found loving forever homes through our rescue program. They are featured to showcase some of the wonderful Keeshond foster dogs that have been adopted from Southern California Keeshond Rescue, Inc. (SCKR).

Thank your for your interest in adopting a rescue Keeshond. Where are you located? You should contact the Keeshond rescue group that is closest to you and get on their waiting list. If you have not done it yet, be sure to ask for an adoption application, so you can start the adoption process. That way, they can put you on their waiting list and let you know when they get a dog that they think might be a good match for you.

We limit adoptions to the Southern California area. 

At this time, we do not have adoptable Keeshond rescue dogs who are ready for permanent placement. As we evaluate new fosters for placement, we will consider adoption applications on file to match with each dog's individual needs. 

COVID-19 update: We are closely monitoring the COVID-19 situation and taking it very seriously. At this time, we will be keeping our rescue dogs in their foster homes and suspending home visits and meet and greets until the COVID-19 situation has changed. Please continue to submit adoption applications and we will resume home visits and meet and greets when the Shelter-in-Place directive has passed.

Are you ready to make a lifetime commitment to a Keeshond rescue dog? If you are interested in adopting one of our foster dogs, the first step is to complete an adoption application. Southern California Keeshond Rescue works with potential adopters to find each dog the right forever home. We foster the dogs in the homes of volunteers, who include them as a part of the family. We have all rescue dogs examined by a veterinarian, spayed/neutered, immunized and tested for heart worms. We provide treatment for known illnesses or medical problems on a case by case basis. Visit our website at http://www.foreverkees.org to learn more about our adoption process and to submit your application.

On behalf of the Keeshonden we serve - thank you for your interest in adopting a Keeshond. We look forward to hearing from you! Please visit our Facebook page too!

Southern California Keeshond Rescue, Inc. (SCKR).
www.foreverkees.org

animal.description:
Meet Ginger! She’s a 2-3 year old shepherd mix that was saved from the shelter. Ginger is a very pretty golden/red color with the sweetest black licorice nose. Her photos do not do her justice, she’s a “must see” in person.

Ginger was turned in by her person following a scuffle with their other dog and she has displayed food protection so she needs to be an only dog and would appreciate the time and space to finish her meals.

Did someone say “play”?! Ginger really enjoys her toys and would love someone to play ball with or even go jogging (check out her video where’s she enjoying a good game of Kong keep away). Ginger can be "a lot of dog" for a petite/slight person and she responds very well to males (we think she prefers a deeper voice and larger stature but it's a bit of a mystery).

Ginger would be the absolute best companion to a single person or a couple that appreciated her as a member of the family. She's been unpredictable around small children so teenage or older would be better suited to her energy. She’s not demanding but does love attention and is quick to learn. Ginger just wants to be loved by someone that is kind and will treat her like the special girl she is.

Ginger is fully house trained, spayed, micro chipped, heartworm negative and current on vaccines.

If a "forever" situation is not your thing, perhaps Ginger could hang out with you until her forever person comes along. Fostering would get her out of boarding and into a home routine. 

To apply to foster or meet Ginger for possible adoption please go to our website and fill out an application.

www.ninjapawsrescue.org

animal.description:
Boyd was surrendered to a shelter for killing chickens.  He was born in January of 2018. He came into rescue weighing 67lbs, and is now at a healthy weight, and is reportedly a Great Pyrenees Anatolian Shepherd mix.  "Anipyrs" are a nice mix of the two breeds - you get the gentle demeanor of the pyr and the short coat of the Anatolian Shepherd.  Since they are both guarding breeds, socialization and training is important.  Boyd is very gentle, and a little timid with new people at first, but warm up quickly. He is doing great walking on a leash.  Boyd would do best in a home with another dog to play with.  He is unproven around cats.  He also does not like being crated, so someone who works from home, and has time to teach him to be comfortable in a crate at home would be the best fit for him.   His tongue was somehow injured and has a split in it,  but all his teeth are fine.  It does not hinder him from eating.  He would do best in an adult only home; he can be growly with children. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted dogs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees and Pyr mixes are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Boyd will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a 6' securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Boyd can get out of a 4' fenced yard.  He would also be eligible as a walk only dog, meaning he is walked for exercise and potty time.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Online Adoption Application 

**Please read the full bio for Cooper ** Meet Cooper. Isn't he handsome? The pictures are great but honestly don't do him justice of just how handsome he is. He is 60 pounds of smushy gray fur with a white-tipped tail, paws, & belly. He has the cutest little underbite. Cooper is looking for his forever home - one who is dedicated to just Cooper as he needs to be the only pet in the home. Cooper is housetrained & crate trained - he enjoys a treat-filled kong or bone while chilling on his bed. Recently he hasn't needed to be crated (his foster mom does remove things that would be tempting to chew in his space). He is a smart boy - in his first home, he completed quite a bit of training. He can sit, leave it, lay down, recall, & stay! He is a strong boy & needs an experienced handler that will work on his manners & leash skills. In his original home, Cooper lived with 10 & 12 year-old boys from the time he was 8 weeks old until he was 11 months old & he loved them very much. He is both active AND chill - he likes to lie down beside you as well as run & do the zoomies in the yard. Chasing a ball or stick is his favorite pastime. When he is done, he's ready to lounge. A DNA test was done which says he is a mixture of Labrador Retriever, American Staffordshire Terrier, hound, & Chinese Shar Pei.If Cooper is so amazing, why was he returned to the rescue? Cooper was loved & cared for from the time he is adopted at 8 weeks of age until he had to return to the rescue at 11 months of age. He was adopted into a home with a 2 year-old dog who was also a Pawfect Match dog. She loved him as a puppy, but gradually indicated that she no longer wanted another dog to live with her, as she would prefer to be the queen of the castle. They both had high energy play styles & a few play sessions became too escalated & difficult to break up, with neither dog relenting. Cooper didn't take kindly to being told no by her, & continued to assert himself. She then didn't take kindly to being ignored. It caused a stressful situation for both dogs. Because of this, we have decided Cooper needs to be the only pet in a furever home.
Cooper needs to know he has a place to be calm & that no other dogs might get in his business. He is not going to be a candidate for a dog park or doggie daycare. It would put him an unpredictable situation, undoing the confidence, training, & self control that are important to his success.
***Cooper is the 'pawfect' match for a household with no other pets looking for a wonderful, housetrained dog with so much to offer. Cooper needs a home with a true FENCED yard (with a wooden privacy fence) so that he can burn off the young dog energy & play in an environment without the ability to get into trouble. Although Cooper has received a great deal of training, he will need an adopter who will commit to ongoing training. Could You be that 'pawfect' match? Could you be the furever home for Cooper?

Online Adoption Application 
Tarzan is a handsome hound mix looking for his true forever home. He is leggy guy who is around 65 pounds. He is a sweet boy who loves to give his foster human a hug. He is house-trained, neutered & up to date on all vet care. Tarzan is a bit anxious so he needs time to warm up to strangers, especially men. Patience and love will be the key for Tarzan - & a bit of medication (Fluoxetine aka Prozac - he takes this daily & does better on it than off). He doesn't love being in a crate so needs patience with that as well & would prefer to not be in one. He does not use one in his foster home. He does well with other dogs although they aren't a necessity - he has loved playing with the dogs in his foster home & previously enjoyed going to a dog park in his first home. He also did pretty well at doggie daycare. The staff at the daycare described him as cautious at first, but loving, & eventually opened up. Tarzan needs a furever family who is patient & dedicated to him, even with his eccentricities, for all of his life - dedicated to his shy nature, dedicated to seeking training & to whatever his care entails. An ideal home for Tarzan would be on the quieter side...one with a human who is home quite a bit...a fenced yard would be great - he isn't ultra-energetic but likes the safety of a yard. He has completed some training & his general manners are pretty good. Tarzan is a loving boy who enjoys snuggles & belly rubs. Could YOU be his pawfect match?

Tucker is a lab/shepherd mix who gives you his whole heart once he knows he can trust you.  He doesn't show well with strangers, but transitioned well and quickly into the shelter with all his new people friends.  He is a large dog with lots of energy.   He has lived with young children and we are told he lived successfully with cats and did o.k. with other respectful dogs, but was nervous at first.  We have not tested him ourselves with cats or children, and have only experienced him between a fence line with other dogs, which he enjoys to run the fence line with.  

Tucker is neutered, microchipped, and completed vaccinated.  He tested negative for all tick-borne illnesses, as well as negative for heartworm disease.  

Tucker loves to see all his human friends come in on shift to let him out and love him up.  He really loves people, but does get scared around new people at first due to lack of socialization during the first year of his life.  Some regular socialization will help him get past this behavior.  He is a big strong fella who requires an active home.

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE: We will only be adopting Shey Shey to a local family as she needs to stay close so that we can offer assistance with her acclimating to her new home/enviornment.

 "Shey Shey" is one of our "Three Little Bears".  She is now almost a year old and is a Shepherd mix.  At only 2-weeks old, she and her litter mates were found near a river trapped in a fishing net and were dying.  Thanks to the dedication and love of our local Veterinarian "Shey Shey" survived and is with us today in all her glory.

Shey Shey has a very introverted personality.  She is shy and slow to meet new people.  Once you sit with her and she has a chance to meet you on her terms, she is an absolute love pie.  She loves to cuddle and she loves to stay close.  She will do best in a calm household with human companions that have a more introverted personality. She gets along well with most dogs and really needs to have a dog companion in her new home. She is a great size at around 40 pounds.

Shey Shey needs a home without younger children, and definitely no cats.

Most of our dogs require a fully fenced yard, this does depend on the individual dogs needs and safety requirements.  

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

Visit our website to fill out an Adoption Application  http://www.wagsequimwa.com

Adoption donation fee $350  (Please understand this adoption donation goes towards helping all the dogs we rescue)

animal.description:
LOVE BUG NEEDS A FOSTER OR LOVING FOREVER HOME!!!
Fosters make it possible for Dogs XL to save and care for homeless and abandoned dogs! To learn about fostering dogs like Love Bug, please contact us at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/volunteer/foster

Name: Love Bug

Breed: Boerbel/Bulldog/Bullmastiff Mix 

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: 95 pounds

Currently Living at: Local Foster

 
Meet Love Bug! Love Bug is a very sweet and affectionate mastiff mix. To be precise, LB's DNA test revealed that she's 75% Boerboel, 12.5% standard Bulldog and 12.5% Bullmastiff!

Bug has a super cute tail nubbin and her whole body wiggles when she's happy, which is nearly all of the time! She’s looking for a family who would love to take her on a hike or out for a swim (there’s nothing cuter than a Love Bug splashing about, rolling in the sand and surf!) Love Bug adores other dogs, but isn't always great at taking their cues when they're done playing, so she would do best with another playful dog and a dog-savvy adopter who can help her learn how to play appropriately. 

This darling girl is strong, and definitely needs some basic manners and leash training. She is also a typical mastiff and would do best with a very experienced adopter who's familiar with guardian breeds as she can be fear reactive to strangers (especially men) and exhibits some guarding behaviors. Bug is muzzle trained for everyone's safety and would love an adopter who will continue to work with her to teach her that strangers aren't as scary as she thinks, and who will manage introductions very safely. Bug is an eager student and excited to learn! If you give her your heart, she promises to be a loyal companion for years to come.

Bug needs a home with no young children, and she is not a good fit for a family with cats. Ask us about Love Bug today!

Love Bug needs a foster or a loving forever home to lavish love and attention on her. Please open your heart and home to Love Bug!


The adoption fee for this dog is $300, which includes the cost of heartworm treatment and routine vetting, including vaccinations and spay/neuter.

 

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out the application online at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/adopt/adoption-questionnaire

 

Thank you for considering adoption and helping to save a life!
 

Please visit us online at www.DogsXLRescue.org

animal.description:
We are looking for a very special adopter or foster for Sage. Sage is a 2 year old, 60lb American bulldog mix of sorts. When she originally came to us from the shelter she had a terrible case of pneumonia and as she began to heal we quickly discovered there was more than what met the eye with her. Sage was diagnosed with diabetes shortly after and has finally reached a point where her glucose is regulated with proper care. Caring for Sage’s diabetes is easy, she receives two insulin injections a day and eats a prescription diet. Her insulin is roughly $35 every other month and her prescription food is around $130 monthly from Chewy. 

Sage absolutely loves all humans and wants nothing more than to go for a short walk before cuddling up on the couch for the long night of binging Netflix. Sage is good with children and is very gentle. Sage had been thought not to like other dogs but has been working on forming a friendship with the calm dog in her foster home. Given the right amount of time, she may be able to live with another calm, older dog, but cannot be with cats. 

Sage is looking for the perfect forever home or even a foster home without other animals. Could that be with you! Diabetes is easy to manage and we would be able to answer any questions you might have!

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Sage would prefer to be the only pet in your life.

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Pepper.  She is a 2 year old Terrier/Cattle Dog mix who weighs 40 lbs. 

Pepper loves her people.  She really would love a home where she got to spend her time being with her person.  She is very sweet and loving.  Pepper is also very playful and loves to run around the yard playing with her toys and the other dogs!  She is a lot of fun.  

Pepper would like a home where she has active owners who will play with her, rub her belly, and spend time with her.  She would do best with another male dog her size as she doesn't do well when left alone but does better when left with a dog friend.  Pepper lives with older kids and does great with them (age 7-12).   She lives with a female and a male dog but does much better with the male dog.  

Pepper is crate, leash, and house trained.

Pepper is spayed, microchipped, and current on her vaccines.  Her adoption fee is $175.  

If you would like to adopt Pepper and make her a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Introducing Wednesday, a pretty pit bull mix looking for a patient and loving home! 

She's timid with new people and things but is an affectionate, fun pooch once she knows you and settles in. Wednesday will thrive in a home with an experienced dog owner. All it takes is some time, a calm voice, easy demeanor, and plenty of treats and she'll open up to you and let you into her world. 

All this little girl wants is a warm, safe couch and a best friend she can put her trust in. Wednesday will be your loyal companion every single day of the week. She's more than happy to be by your side through thick and thin. 

Wednesday is spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped. She is staying in Belton, Missouri, right now but transport is available to the right home. With her adoption you'll get the ongoing support of The Pet Connection for her training needs! 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 any day of the week for more information on Wednesday!

#thepetconnectionks #adoptdontshop #adoptWednesdaytoday

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center located at 417 N Rawhide Suite H, Olathe, KS 66061.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Forever home wanted!!!! Meet Romeo!!!!

Romeo is a ten year, 55 lbs. lab hound mix that adores everyone. Romeo lived his whole life in paradise (Kauai, Hawaii). Sadly his Mom got sick and had to leave the Island for her medical care and couldn't take Romeo with her. As a senior dog on a small Island, Romeo was quickly euth listed by the shelter. When we were alerted to Romeo's situation, Romeo's travel arrangements were quickly made. Romeo had his senior work up done and his lumps removed (just big fatty masses, not cancerous per the biopsy) and is now ready to find a forever home. Romeo is house trained, leash trained, crate trained, rides well in the car, knows some basic commands, gets along well with people and dogs (with proper introductions) and wants nothing more than to please everyone he meets. He's the perfect blend of long walks and cuddling on the couch and is the market for a loving family that will cherish him through his golden years. Could that family be yours? Email dogs@labradorsandfriends.org or fill out our online application at www.labradorsandfriends.org. Romeo is located in Southern California.

animal.description:
** SPECIAL NEEDS DUE TO BEING EXTREMELY SHY **

Male Border Collie Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 04/19/2016

Weight: 50.5 lbs

Children: 16 and over 

Dogs: Yes, REQUIRED 

Cats: Unknown


Linus is a very special boy who will need a patient, quiet, and loving home to help him come out of his shell and gain confidence. In his first couple of years this bashful boy was not often exposed to every day life situations, if at all and perhaps he was even a stray at some point. 

Since arriving at TVR, he has become more confident and secure in his surroundings. He genuinely loves to play with the other dogs and feels much safer in their presence and with a pack. He is becoming more comfortable when interacting with people but it still takes a long time for him warm up to new people. In spite of his fears, he does know how to walk on leash and seems to be reasonably house-trained although accidents can occur during any new and/or stressful situation.

Linus belongs in a home with at least one other dog who is super friendly and confident to take the lead and show him the way. He will benefit from an outgoing counterpart that will help him find his courage. His human can help soothe Linus by brushing him (he loves it) and filling his dog bed with cozy blankets before tucking him into bed. 

We are not 100% sure what incident occurred to make the world an intimidating place for Linus, but we know in our hearts that with the right person by his side and the security of a home he will learn to feel safe and at ease. He will finally be able to take a breath and live a happy peaceful life which he deserves. 

Are you ready to give this sweet, gentle and shy boy the home he has been waiting so patiently for?


*HEARTWORM UPDATE: Linus has completed his heart worm treatment and is ready to go to his new home! It is very important for Linus to be kept on a monthly Heartworm preventative (such as Heartgard Plus) and not miss a dose. Linus will need to be taken to the adopters primary vet in 9 months (approximately June 10th, 2021) to be retested for Heartworm Disease.

animal.description:
This sweet boy is Alexander.  He is a 1.5 year old lab/kelpie mix who weighs 50 lbs.  Alexander was rescued as a puppy from the shelter.  

Alexander is a very sweet boy who does great meeting new people.  Alexander would like a home where he has a yard to run and play in.  He will need a family willing to give him lots of love and affection and playtime.  He will need a 6ft fence as he's very athletic and can jump a shorter fence especially because he'd be motivated to do so by other passing dogs.  

Alexander does live with another dog currently in his foster home but does struggle meeting new dogs.   If introduced properly, Alexander is good with other dogs however he gets a little overwhelmed in a large play group of dogs so wouldn't do well at the dog park or a multi-dog household.   Alexander is very reactive on the leash to other dogs but has no problem with people. For this reason, he would do best with an experienced owner. 

Alexander is house trained. He does not love his crate but he is working on that in his foster home and will need continued work in his forever home.  He currently sleeps in his crate and is crated when left. 

Alexander is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Alexander and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Pint sized fun!!Meet cutie Coco!
Coco is likely three years old and about 45#. She's a big personality in an itty bitty pitty body. Coco is a fun dog to have around. You'll catch her zooming around the yard, romping with her doggie friends, and playing fetch. Coco also appreciates cuddles with her humans.
Though Coco has a clean bill of health, you may notice the bump on her cheek. Coco has visited multiple veterinarians and they all concur that the bump is from a previous trauma. They also indicated that because it doesn't bother her, they dont recommend unnecessary cosmetic surgery. She has had a biopsy and confirmation that it is NOT cancer. Though we will never know what Coco experienced, we know her future forever family will love her just the way she is.
Coco is too interested in cats, so no meow meows. She would do great in a home with or without another dog. Children 10+.
To meet her, call (530) 824-1985. You can also submit an application at http://www.secondchancepetrescue.org/adopt/

animal.description:
3 year old Logan became too much for his the woman who owned him. She worked long hours and as Logan grew and became stronger and more energetic, she realized she could not provide the type of home he deserved. Broken hearted, but determined to do the right thing for the dog she loved, she turned to GSROC for help.

Logan is now with GSROC and we have promised to help him find an active and loving home. He is a young guy with tons of energy and strong. Smart as a whip, he loves to keep busy and learn new things. He will thrive in a home that provides him with structure and commits to his training.

Logan is learning to live with structure and limits. He has developed certain ideas of what behavior is appropriate. Our volunteers are spending time teaching him that he does not get to be in charge. Check out one of his training videos!

Please go to our website and complete an adoption application at:

/https://www.gsroc.org/application/

An adoption counselor will contact you to go over your application and assist you in determining which dog may be best for your particular situation.

Scooter is between six and eight years old and was tossed out like yesterday’s garbage. He wound up in a small town shelter and lucky for him, we were notified. Scooter came to us with back end issues and when we got him to our vet it was discovered he had a broken pelvis. This is not a new injury and he must have been in great pain when the break happened. Because of this Scooter has mobility issues and has to have his bladder expressed several times a day and doesn’t know when he has to poop. He is such a sweetheart and it breaks our heart to think that no one will want to adopt him. Thanks to some pug angels, Scooter will be getting a cart and we can’t wait to see him wheel around the yard. Please consider giving this sweet boy a real forever home. He deserves the best life has to offer!!

animal.description: Hi, my name is Stormy. I am almost 9 years old and spent 8 of those years in a commercial breeding facility where it was my job to have lots and lots of puppies. One day last year, some nice people came and took me on a really long ride to a place called a foster home. I had never been anywhere before and everything was so different and new - wow, was I scared! When I got there, I saw a doctor who said that I had something called heart worm disease and would need treatment. So I had to stay very quiet and calm for a few months. But I was a very good girl and now all the heart worms are gone and I'm healthy! Foster mom says that I'm a very calm and gentle girl. Foster mom says that she can't wait to see my true personality and inner Shibatude emerge now that I'm healthy and can hang out with the other dogs. For now, I am pretty shy and still learning that I can trust humans. Loud noises and sudden movements are particularly frightening to me, so I would do best in a quiet home without small children. My foster family has been trying to teach me to walk on this thing called a leash, but I really just don't understand it. So it would be best if my forever home has a securely fenced yard. When I first got to my foster home, I was pretty shy about going potty, especially outside with all of the strange scary noises. So my foster parents taught me to use potty pads inside so I didn’t have accidents! Now that I am brave enough to be off the leash In the yard more, I’m learning that I don't have to be quite as shy about doing my business out there! I really like my foster siblings a lot, especially the little puppy that lives here too. It would be great if my forever home had another dog to help show me the ropes! If you live in the midwest and are interested in adopting me, please visit www.savingshibas.com/adopt for more information and to dowload an application to become approved as an adopter.

animal.description: Peach is a sweet and goofy girl, but she does take a while to fully warm up to new people. At only 2 years old, it is apparent that she had never learned to properly interact with humans or other animals. Peach is incredibly dog social, but she sometimes has difficulty reading other dog's play cues. She also has possession aggression with other dogs and due to guarding tendencies, we feel she would do best in a quiet home as an only dog. She has passed a preliminary cat test. She walks well on a leash but does not like to meet other dogs while leashed due to barrier issues. She is kennel trained, however, she has weather phobia and will try to escape her crate to be near her people. Peach is in need of a 6 foot privacy fence as she is capable of climbing a 6ft chain link fence. Given her trust issues and collar sensitivities, we feel she would be best in a home with older or no children. Peach is wanting to find that perfect family who is willing to take a chance on a young broken soul and give her the time and space she needs to build up trust. Once she trusts you, she will reward you with loyal companionship, a strong bond, the absolute best snuggles in the world.

animal.description:
4/22/2020 update - our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit.  If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm Viva's second born, so I'm Lara, formerly known as Baby Girl 2!  My birthday is 5/28/2019 (4:32 am).  I'm growing up nicely and am ready for my new home, just like my siblings.  I'm very special and very busy.  There's so much for me to see and learn and do.  I love playing with my buddies inside and outside.  I have a blast in the pool and climbing mountains in the yard.  I'm a girl so I'm a bossy little thing.  I'm the smallest of the pack but I'm definitely feisty.  I'm going to be a spectacular, loving and adventurous companion.

You can see more about my story on the Utah's Perfect Pointers facebook page:  https://www.facebook.com/pg/UtahsPerfectPointers/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2441619882523003

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
NO KIDS FENCE REQUIRED

Bagel may look like a super sweet dog, but he has some major behavior issues and resource guards people and other dogs on occasion. He MUST have an experienced dog owner who knows how to handle dogs with behavior issues. A dog trainer or behaviorist would be best. You cannot have him in a corner where he feels that he has no way out or he will growl, bark and show his teeth and it will scare you. He has been living with a dog trainer for over a year now and has gotten adopted several times and he was always returned because the adopters could not handle his personality. At his current foster home he does really well and has minimal issues but that took a good amount of time. If you are willing to put in the work you'll get back a hilariously animated, very goofy, super handsome, and personable dog. Bagel is crate trained, house broken, a mild puller on walks, has no major medical issues or medication, and can be surprisingly good with guest visitors. Right now, he lives with a dog trainer, another adult and 3 dogs. Bagel's favorite activities include walks, playing with his dog friends, and hanging out in the yard. Bagel's ideal home has one or two adults, has confident active dogs to play and interact with, a yard, plus patient and experienced dog owners.

Please do not fill out an application for Bagel unless you have thoroughly read and understand this bio and his issues. We know he is cute but that doesn't mean he would be an easy dog to handle in your home. We do want what is best for Bagel and the right fit for your home. and that is why we are being completely honest with what he needs. Absolutely no kids and no cats.

Bagel is part of our monthly special! His adoption fee is only $100!

If you are interested in meeting Bagel, complete the Adoption Application on our website at www.NeedyPaws.org and we will contact you. Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Bagel 's adoption fee is $100.00, which includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter. 2/2/21 5:36 PM

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THIS GUY'S DESCRIPTION!! 
As of 12/31/2020, Shorty is still looking for his forever home.
Shorty is not a first-time hybrid owner kinda guy, he has to have a highly knowledgeable owner with a wolf proof enclosed to be able to qualify to adopt him. We don't want to see anyone or their pets get hurt or to see Shorty run off and get hurt himself. As of 05/03/2020, our dear Shorty turned 1-year old and is still with us. We have tried a few placements, fosters, and adopters but none have worked and he has been returned every time. He is trying out to be the alpha male so would work well with other large female dogs but will fight with other males and could do serious harm to smaller dogs. Very independent, headstrong, intelligent, and well mattered once he gets to know and trust a person. He will listen and mind you once he trusts you but he does have that wolf personality and attitude so trust is going to take a lot of time and patients. We're definitely wanting an owner that has a lot of knowledge working with and owning wolfdogs. He is a Siberian Husky Wolf Hybrid mix so he can be hardheaded and stubborn at times. He's large and strong so he may not do well with kids he will mow them over if they get in his way. Also would not advise leaving him unsupervised around any small animal including smaller dogs these are prey and snacks to him. He will need to be on a mix of kibble and loads of raw meats and is very high energy so lots of exercises are advised to keep him out of trouble. You're welcome to email the shelter for any other info.

Tempo of the Dog Rescue is a foster-based rescue out of Saint Charles, MO. 

What does that mean? That means we do not have a facility for dogs to stay at. We save lives thanks to people all over the metro Saint Louis area opening their homes to dogs in need. 

We are ALWAYS seeking foster homes for dogs so we can continue to save lives. The rescue provides what you need to take care of the dog. Crate, food, vetting, necessary medications, etc. The foster period can last a few weeks to a few months depending on the dog. Our goal is to match you with a dog that fits your household to make it the best possible experience for you.

animal.description:
This Beauty is looking for her forever home!Sweet Senior Edie is 10 years young - but still has plenty of pep in her step. She is very alert to everything around her and will follow you around the house to keep track of where her people are going. She loves her toys and bones but does not like to share - we don't blame her for that! She does allow her humans to take them away from her nicely.

Edie lives with two other dogs and she does fine. They are not best friends but they like to co-exist with one another. The other dogs have learned to give Edie her space. She is crate and house trained (but prefers to not be in her crate). She knows her basic commands and loves puzzle toys!

Edie does have DCM and gets medication twice a day. She also gets fish oil and CBD oil supplements for her joints to keep her young and moving! Edie would love a forever home to spend her golden years with!

This fabulous foster is a Doberman Rescue Minnesota foster dog.

Please read all adoption steps and policies carefully on our website. http://dobermanrescueminnesota.com/adoption-steps/

Qualified adopters are within the approved adoption area, and Adopter will be requested to visit this foster dog at the foster family home. Our foster families are generally located within a 250 mile radius of Minneapolis, MN.

All DRM dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, health checked, microchipped, 4DX tested, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention. 2/2/21 5:36 PM

animal.description:
Emma and Ruby
Coonhound Sisters (Bonded Pair/Adopt as Pair)
About 4 years old
50 pounds
VISIBLE ABOVE-GROUND FENCE REQUIRED
LOCAL LOUISVILLE AREA ADOPTIONS /
--includes Jeffersonville, Clarksville, New Albany in Indiana
$300.00 plus 6% Tax for Adoption Fee/For Pair 

"I'd Walk a Thousand Miles For You" Emma and Ruby

We guess we'll never know how many miles these sisters walked, but they walked and they walked and they walked. And by the time a wonderful woman and her husband found them Emma and Ruby's paws were swollen, red and blistered. We don't even know where they gathered the energy. Their bones could easily be counted. They acted like they'd never eaten a meal in their lives. They were terribly neglected physically. Medical complications arose because of their neglect but the Good Samaritan who found these babies hung in with them. And we mean hung in! It isn't always convenient to be a Good Samaritan. A person who sees a pet in need and decides they can't turn their back. But the payoff for the heart ... well, you can't put it into words but you can sure put it into pictures. Look at Emma and Ruby now! <3

The only thing better than this amazing picture of these darling sisters is that last picture we can't wait to post. The day they find their forever home! Ruby and Emma are approximately 4 years old around 58 pounds. They've done amazingly well with the other dogs and they are just wonderful with humans. Love kept these two sisters together and maybe that hope and prayer of a forever family is what kept them going. <3 <3 

To adopt write to: adoptions@shamrockpets.com (Louisville, Ky Local)

cc 08/0`/2019

She is being fostered in the Jefferson City area

animal.special_needs_notes:
Wanda has a birth defect, so she's extra special without a tail.  She had some
issues with her bowels, chronic diarrhea and frequent attempts to go.  We asked for a consult at the University of Missouri, but it was cancelled when the pandemic hit. 

Because Wanda was exhibiting all symptoms of EPI, I ordered an EPI test kit. It was not an absolute definitive positive result, but felt we needed to try something.  So, Wanda got started on enzymes, and after just two weeks, there was marked improvement!  There were some hiccups along the way, and we just felt there was still an issue.  When the University called to reschedule the appt from spring, we jumped on the chance to have Wanda looked at by a GI specialist.  Wanda had lab work and urinalysis,  her EPI test wasn’t redone - everything came back normal.  Now we were really scratching our heads.  If not EPI, then what?

We were encouraged to follow up with the University’s internal medicine dept. on 10/29.  They did an MRI and x-ray.  Wanda definitely has a congenital defect (on the outside and inside).  Wanda’s colon is larger than it should be.  Also, where her pelvis and spinal cord meet is compressed.  Her x-rays definitely do not look like regular x-rays.  The vet could see that Wanda’s intestines were full of feces.  She had issues that she was not able to empty her bowels which explains why she was always trying to go.  The vet started her on lactulose and a compound medication (both liquid) to be given twice daily.  The vet prescribed her hydrolyzed food which will help her with digestion.  The vet also said there’s minimal nerve function.

animal.description:
Moose was found as a stray in a ditch in rural Indiana.  We estimate him to be about 3 years old.  While at the shelter, he bonded quickly with some of the staff, but not others, making him unadoptable based on their requirements.  We had an experienced Great Pyrenees "Pyrent" meet with Moose to assess him, who noted the shelter environment was extremely stressful for him, and that being in a foster home would be a better test of his personality. He felt he was a good dog, who needed some structure, and that he was a typical young male Great Pyrenees.  Moose has made himself right at home in his foster home.  He is very loving with his foster family, loves to play with the resident dogs and is well behaved with them.  He is crate trained too, but does not need to be crated when you are gone.   Moose gets along well with their cat also.  He rides well in cars.  If you are looking for a snuggle buddy, Moose is the boy for you!  He would probably do best in a household with adults only, and supervision with children is always recommended when a dog is present.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 18 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Moose will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
Please read the entire bio before contacting us with questions. Send us an email requesting an application to start the adoption process-- ADOPT@ALMOSTHOMENM.ORG

**If you are requesting an application make sure you add our address to your safe sender list or watch your junk/spam emails. 

For more photos please visit our Facebook page.   http://www.facebook.com/pages/Almost-Home-New-Mexico/203840136304815 

Approximate DOB 11/03/2015

Size - About 50 lbs

History- A litter of puppies were turned into a rural shelter. Mom was an American Staffordshire Terrier and dad was unknown. The puppies were scheduled to go to an out of state rescue however that rescue backed out at the last minute. The puppies risked being sent back to the shelter for euthanasia so we agreed to bring them here. 

Temperament- Initially- Very standoffish, shy, and weary. Czr would not do good in a busy home with a lot of visitors. Once he bonds he is a big ol' lap dog-- he loves laps, cuddling on the couch, and hugs. Once he has bonded he is very sweet, playful, and happy who loves his toys. He does look intimidating because he is so serious but he is a shy guy who just wants love..   

Energy Level- Mid to lower level energy- loves to play chase and wrestle with the other dogs (he is with Jacques, Taffy, and Piquin). They wrestle, play tug, play chase, and just have fun but he would really love to have his own person to love and cuddle with on the couch.

Dogs/Cats- Good with the other dogs and cats

Housetrained- House trained perfectly using a dog door. There have been no mistakes at all.

This guy is so handsome, loving, and gentle with his family. However, gaining his trust will take some time and treats. He is one of those dogs that will require several visits before transitioning to a new home and then should be kept on leash for at least a week or two. Once he bonds he is the most amazingly beautiful, happy, goofy boy ever. He is stocky but not large. He would love a family to love and call his very own who he can sprawl out on the couch with. He will make someone an amazing pet as he bonds strongly and becomes an amazing protector.

Adoption fee is a donation to the rescue - he is neutered, has been given all age appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, 3 yr rabies vacc, HW tested, collar and tags, training information, and all the support you need.

Send us an e-mail to adopt@almosthomenm.org  requesting an application to adopt this sweetie!! Animals are seen by appointment only. An application must be submitted to us prior to making an appointment.
We do give a discount when adopting multiple pets.

Visit our main website www.almosthomenm.org
Follow us on Facebook Facebook page http://www.facebook.com/pages/Almost-Home-New-Mexico/203840136304815
If you would like to help care for this homeless baby while they await their new home please send a donation   Almost Home NM - PO Box 772- Peralta, NM 87042   or via paypal - "Tools"- "Send Money"- "Friends and Family" - Email address adopt@almosthomenm.org

animal.description:
ACE IS NOT AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. ACE IS A SPECIAL NEEDS PUP WHO NEEDS SPONSORSHIP

Hi folks, Darling Ace here, I'm about 11 years old and weigh ten pounds. I tend to enjoy a low key predictable lifestyle. It's best to take baby steps when making changes in my life. I'm a very loyal fellow. I also might like another small "low key" friend to pal around with. I just live for one or two little squeaky toys. My favorite is a long neck brontosaurus. I'm not much of a jumper, but I have learned how to use puppy stairs. I love my walks and do great on a leash, my back end sometimes chooses its own direction, but that doesn't stop me. My foster family thinks it's kinda cute. I take several naps a day to keep my peppy alert personality going. I like to be within eye or earshot of a family member. My eyes, ears, and smeller work well. I've had no problem adapting to my family's schedule. Potty skills are good in my current foster home, I am an indoor dog. In a new home, it might take a day or two for me to know where and when to do my business, but I'm a quick learner. Here I have access to the outdoors and a short/low ramp to walk out to the yard.

At Bichon Rescue of Orange County, our commitment to our pups does not waiver when they have special needs. These special needs pups are less likely to be adopted for reasons of age, health or behavior. We have amazing volunteers committed to fostering these pups until the end but we need sponsors to help with funding all of their needs. Won't you consider supporting Lily by setting up a monthly sponsorship? Even the smallest amount will help. As a Senior Sponsor we will send you photos and updates on Lily. If you can find it in your heart to help Lily or one of our other seniors, please copy and paste this link in your browser: https://bichonrescueoc.org/sponsorship.
