animal.description:
No Phone Calls or Emails -Due to this dogs past behavior, he cannot go to a home with children or anyone over 50 years old. 

LAST CHANCE FOR ADOPTION:  When Bradley came from the shelter in Aug 2019 he had some serious health issues. His ears were chronically neglected to the point he had to have ear ablation in one ear. On top of all of that he had heart worm disease which had affected his liver. However, the rescue got him treated for heartworms and his liver returned to normal. He is now heart worm negative. We also got his ear ablation done and still battle his other ear. As long as he remains on hypoallergenic food and stay on top of his ear infection he is doing okay.

When Bradley came to rescue the shelter said he seemed to be a nice dog.  But, he was not so nice and for a few months later acted out wanting to bite and jump up on you when he didn't like what was happening. He did bite the rescue lady back in March of this year after his ear surgery. Since that time we finally have gotten him to accept an alpha structured environment.

Bradley cannot live in a home with any children and is best suited for middle age adults in case he does bite. He isn't biting us now, he has been here long enough that he trusts us. The foster mom can correct him, massage him, medicate his one ear and ruffle his feathers. He is finally doing better with dogs so perhaps being an only dog or with one submissive dog would be best.   Bradley is still working on house manners. He needs someone willing to give him a chance and not quit on him when he acts out. He can be a loving sweet dog in the right hands.

Adoption fee:  $350.

animal.description:
Meet Spot!  This handsome fellow is looking for a new home after he was sadly abandoned by his previous owner..  He is very strong and energetic and would benefit from some training, so an experienced dog owner that will work with him would be ideal.  Spot is a 4 year old boxer-terrier mix.

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter. We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family’s needs. To achieve this we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adoptees. This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs. Please e-mail Stacy@NAWSUS.org to set up a day and time to meet with Tim, Victoria or Heather, (our dog adoption counselors), and our potential adoptees. Thank you!!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Very sweet goofy girl, makes a great companion.Hi,

I'm Roxie and I hope you are ready to fall in love! My foster mom says I'm the sweetest girl in town !I'm a little shy at first but give me 24 hrs to warmup and you'll feel like we've been together for years. I love my humans, my hobbies include following you around, chewing toys, snuggling and sleeping on the couch, I'm learning the whole walking on the leash thing, I sleep in my kennel at night and do pretty well. Really I'm just a happy lucky girl waiting for my furever home, my perfect family!!

Please contact
app@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog.

You can apply online by clicking on

Application

.

Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations.

Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events.

Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Sally lost her home and her owner due to an accident.  Her owner was injured and could no longer care for her. She has never been around children so we are looking for a child and pet free foster or foster to adopt home. 

Her owner describes her as a gentle giant, active and affectionate, adventurous and playful.  She's loving, caring and sympathetic.  She loves going for walks, being petted, getting attention, exploring, and exercising.  She has lots of energy, is fearless and knows some basic commands.  

"She is absolutely wonderful. It's been an amazing 5 1/2  years. She is so loving and loyal".

But now Sally is suffering from kennel stress.  She never relaxes in her kennel and is starting to have a great deal of anxiety.  It's imperative that we find her a home asap before she starts to truly suffer.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Sally had lived with a small dog, but is easily startled and is not always accepting of other dogs.  She will chase cats, squirrels etc.

Sadly, she is currently off the adoption floor until we can help her.  Some dogs handle a kennel environment without stress or anxiety, others do not fair well.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Angel. I am two years old and a purebred Carolina Dog. I am a very loyal girl and pretty smart too. My ideal home would be with humans (NO CHILDREN) that have calm energy and strong leadership. Because I don't like a lot of excitement, an adult only home would be best for me. I love my humans and prefer to not be left alone for long periods of time. I do get along with other dogs but I can be dog selective at times so proper introductions are needed. My most favorite activity is searching in the yard for lizards, so my ideal home will have a fun back yard for me to play in. But because I love to chase things, it's a good idea that I do not live with a cat. I am good walking on a leash and really like my daily exercise so I am looking for active people like me! I have a very sweet and loving personality to share with the right person - hope that is you!

If you are interested in adopting, please visit the I.C.A.R.E. Dog Rescue website and complete an adoption application: www.icaredogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter shots up to date micro-chip fecal and vet check

animal.description: What do you think of my awesome name? Does it remind you of the precious, beautiful stone? It represents courage and wisdom and I have that in spades. I'm a ton of fun to be around - just ask all my two-legged and four-legged friends! I love a good romp in the playfields with my dog pals, and afterwards some quality one-on-one time with my human friends - with lots of love and attention, of course. Kisses anyone?! But I'm not just all about having fun, I LOVE to learn. I know all my basic commands already, but I'm always ready for more! I'm super motivated and a really hard workerfeeling up to a the challenge to teach me some new tricks? I can't wait! I've been hard at work in the American Kennel Club Canine Good Citizen Shelter Dog training program. I've learned all sorts of cool things to help me become an upstanding member of society! If you adopt me, the shelter will provide us with FREE training classes so that we can take the official test together and I can become CGC certified! I'm a sponsored Dolly's Dream dog and a Fospice pet. Adopt me and all my routine medical care, food, medication and other supplies will be provided by Peggy Adams Animal Rescue League, free of charge. We'll also go home together with an ID tag, leash, collar, harness, training crate, dog bed, toys, training treat bag, food and water bowls and 7 months of pet insurance. Wow, huh?! Lots of goodies for you and me, and even a waived adoption fee! Meet with an Adoption Coordinator to learn more.

animal.description: Penelope. Penelope Cruz. Sweet P! These are all names that friends fondly call this sensitive and loving senior gal. Penelope is ready to leave her past behind her and is looking forward to a future filled with lots of love and belly rubs! She is described by the people who know her best as affectionate, silly, and loyal. As an ahem, distinguished lady, Penelope has experience in a home, and knows a thing or two about couch snuggling, potty breaks, and zoomies in a yard. Penelope would be more than glad to snuggle up and watch a movie with you, or take a leisurely stroll in the neighborhood in the cool mornings or evenings. When she feels happy and safe, Penelope makes the cutest little grunt. Oink oink! She can sometimes be particular about new people but it all comes from a past that she had no control over. As an outside dog, Penelope felt the need to protect her home and family from strangers. Her ideal home would be low traffic, and slow proper intros when there are visitors. She does have the potential to live with another calm, respectful, low-medium energy dog. We would love to introduce you to Penelope if you think she sounds like the dog for you! animal.description: Hi, my name is QUEEN and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Pit Bull Terrier mix. The shelter staff think I am about 10 years old. I have been at the shelter since Sep 09, 2020. Well hello there! I am the lovely Queen. I am loving and affectionate and love to go for walks. I had to come back to the shelter because I did not get along with the other dog on the property. According to my previous owner I know how to sit, stay, and lie down AND I`m crate trained. I`ve never lived around kitties or other dogs, and would prefer to be the ONLY PET in your life. I need a home with teenagers or adults as I can be sensitive about handling. Queen pupdate: Hello there hoomans! Well, I`ve been hanging out in a really cool foster home for a few months now and I`m pretty settled in. A few more things you need to know about me - I am a GREAT watchdog, I will watch out the window all day long and let you know if anything suspicious is happening, like that pesky neighborhood squirrel is getting on the porch again! I love to go for rides in the car, in fact sometimes my foster mom and dad have a hard time convincing me to get out of the car when we get home. I have some aches in my joints so I get special food and treats (I suspect it might be MEDICINE!) to help keep me feeling good, and going for regular walks keeps me from getting too stiff and sore. While I love my foster family, I am ready to find that special home to call my OWN. **** Interested in adopting?? Email dogfoster@thehumanesociety.org !! ****

animal.description:
Austin is a gorgeous, young Pyr with the most luxurious, white, fluffy coat! Before you go falling head over heels for Austin’s drop-dead handsome looks, he wants you to know he’s got some non-negotiable requirements for his new family. Milk bones are a must :) But Austin’s new humans must also understand that he’s been hurt in the past and he is going to need some time and space to earn your trust. Once he feels safe, Austin will reward your patience with loyalty and affection. Nothing makes this boy happier than pleasing his humans. He can be left alone, but the crate makes him very nervous. You will be super impressed with all the commands Austin has mastered such as: heal, stop, let's go, come, sit, wait, paw, down, leave it, drop it, and focus. Austin prefers female dogs, after slow proper introductions but will choose to be with his humans over dogs. He is looking for a home without many visitors and will need to be put in another room if guests do stop by. He is working hard to overcome his fears but his new family should understand that he may never conquer them and that’s ok! A family with breed experience, particularly with fearful dogs, will understand how to set this boy up for success, so he can live the life he deserves with humans he trusts. Due to his past trauma, young kids are a no but cats are a go. If given the right environment, Austin will thrive and reward you with kindness. Once he feels safe, he will quickly become your shadow. Austin will make the Pyrfect family very happy, if they can give him the patience and understanding he needs to thrive. If you sound like what Austin is looking for, apply today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description: This beautiful fur baby's name is Willow and is she approximately 2 years old. She is a very sweet and friendly girl who loves attention. She is currently vaccinated, micro-chipped and heart worm negative. The clinic that originally vaccinated her couldn't tell if she was spayed and because we didn't want to put her through unnecessary spay surgery we decided to wait to see if she went into heat. She hasn't exhibited any signs of going into heat in the year we have had her so we believe she is spayed. If after she is adopted, she should go into heat, we will pay for her spay surgery at a vet of our choosing. Willow would be a great family dog. We believe she is house trained as she waits to go potty until she gets out of her outdoor kennel for exercise.  Willow has a lot of energy and because she is still the "perfect dog" in training, needs some work in some basic training. She knows the sit command but in her excitement to get attention from humans she might jump up and put her paws on them which could be overpowering for small children, therefore, we believe she would be a better fit for families with larger children. She is friendly towards other dogs and we believe she will do great with any dog that is playful in nature with an even tempered personality but would be fine in an only dog family as long as she received a lot of attention from her family and daily exercise. She currently is fostered on property that has a lot of room for exploring. Willow does lose her winter coat starting in the spring so her fur does need to be raked to remove the loosened fur. She seems to enjoy it (and the attention she gets during the process). If you feel this wonderful girl would fit into your lifestyle please email us at arnt_dfw@yahoo.com for a pre-adoption questionnaire which is part of the adoption process. Once reviewed, if it appears your home would be the right fit for her we can schedule a meet and greet. Her adoption fee is $200. animal.description:
Two year old Boxer mix, Hammy, is looking for her Happily Ever After! Hammy was brought here to Colorado from Texas where 2BABR has truly lived up to their name. She has enjoyed living in a loving foster home that has helped her grow and thrive since she joined the 2BABR family. 

Hammy still retains some concerns for small humans, other dogs, and vacuum cleaners (weird, but true!) and thus needs a calm, well structured home without children under the age of 15 or other animals. Hammy has been working hard on basic obedience and responds well to the use of a training collar to assist her with impulse control. Hammy is potty trained, crate trained, and walks very well on a leash. Hammy loves to play catch but resists returning the ball to it's thrower in favor of playing with it and tossing it in the air to herself. Hammmy does require a yard with a privacy fence (6 foot minimum). She is treat motivated but her favorite "reward" is a belly scratch and hearing the words "good girl!" 

Hammy needs a strong leader in her life and one who will continue to work with her on training, manners, and structure. Please apply today if you think Hammy could live her Happily Ever After in your home and heart! 

*BSL Restrictions apply!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
Algebra spent his life in a plywood box, in the hot florida sun,  he was forced to lay in his own urine he had to have some surgery to correct the damage from urine burns. When he could no longer stand he was dumped at a high kill animal control facility, his back legs so stiff, the hunters said he was useless...they said he was old...that was their excuse for his stiff body and emaciated condition....he also had a flesh wound  from a bullet.  He is in great health now.

He is a great companion and attaches mostly to one person. He is very affectionate to his person, once he knows they are his friend.

He likes girl dogs and wants to play w other male dogs but is too dominant so he would be best in a home where he is the only dog.

Because of the cruelty he endured and because he was used ( abused) as a hunting dog he would be best in a quiet home.

all adopters must have a securely fenced yard, be a stable home owner and have a past pet who a veterinarian can verify you took good care of.

Algebra would be the perfect pet for the right person,  he loves to play fetch...call audrey 484-844-0374   thank you.

animal.description:
Felix and his brother Oscar came to us from a rural shelter in central VA.  They were surrendered along with 3 siblings and from what we were told, all 5 of them had been kept in cages outdoors.  We were also told that Felix is 11 years old, although that is hard to believe when we see him playing with the young puppy in his foster home.  Both Oscar and Felix were adopted, but while Oscar is happily in his forever home, Felix was returned to the rescue because he was having trouble with his house-training in his new home,  even though he appears to be housetrained in his foster home.    Anyone who adopts him will have to be willing to work through this issue with him.

Felix loves attention and would probably be happiest as the only dog in the home.  He is fine with some dogs in his foster home, but not with others.  He likes to be outside, but he also loves to cuddle on the couch with his humans.  He is now  about  12 years old weighs about 13 lbs.   He would really love a quiet home of his own where he can live out the rest of his life.  

Oh, and I almost forgot to write that Felix is missing the foot on his back right leg!  You can see it if you look closely at the pictures, but it is really hard to tell.  The vet noticed that he actually has part of a paw pad on the stump that he has, which means that he was born without the foot rather than having had it amputated at some point.  This must be the reason that he has no trouble with missing a foot and it's also the reason that I almost forgot to add it to his description.  It's easy to forget about it because it doesn't bother him.  Sometimes he will hold up the leg that is missing the foot and sometimes he will walk on it.  Either way, it doesn't seem to slow him up much.  

If you like to meet Felix or apply to adopt him, please email cosmozcause@gmail.com

animal.description: Please contact Vivienne (viviennejames@comcast.net) for more information about this pet.Miss Moxie is a 2 year old Feist mix who weighs 20 lbs. She is a sweet but shy little girl who has not had the best beginning to her short life. Moxie was taken to West Tennessee shelter. Even though the shelter was open she was left outside in a plastic crate with a big bag of dog food on top of it. Thank goodness someone noticed the food and the crate and went to bring it inside never thinking there was a dog inside. Imagine how hot Moxie must have been and how scared. She has been in foster care now for a few weeks and has left that life behind. Moxie has learned that people are nice and she is warming up to everyone quickly. Moxie loves to be petted and comes up and puts her front feet on your leg so that you can love on her. She has also learned to sleep on a dog bed beside her foster dad's bed. She is welcome on the bed but seems to prefer her own. She can also be found sitting in her crate relaxing during the day. Moxie is housebroken and can stay loose in the house during the day. She does not bother anything at all. Moxie does love to play and tries to entice her foster brother and sister to play with her. She prefers playing with them over toys. Moxie likes to be outside and it making great strides at walking on a leash. She loves to run around in the fenced in back yard and likes to sun when it is not too hot. A fenced in yard is a must for Moxie as she will not walk on a leash to do her business. She would be good as an only dog as long as she does not have to spend lots of time alone and she would be fine with a similar sized dog her age. If you would like to be considered for her forever home please contact Vivienne at viviennejames@comcast.net or 615-943-7311. APPROVED APPLICATION AND ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED.

animal.description:
If you have every considered adopting a pair of dogs who not only get along wonderful, but who give each other confidence, then we have just the right match for you!

Greta and Sue make each other’s lives so much better.  Sue is blind and while she navigates her world just fine once accustomed to her surroundings, Greta makes everything so much easier for her since Sue has a mate to follow around and give her the confidence she needs in the world.  Additionally, Greta is a super gentle but submissive soul who comes right out of her shell in the presence of Sue.  With Sue and Greta together they are totally different dogs and it is amazing to see!

These girls are both great with other dogs, housebroken and just the sweetest dogs around!   While Sue is good with cats, Greta is not so a home without kitties is ideal.  Both are good with kids but we would prefer a home without children simply because Sue might spook easy with the quick movements and loud sounds of kids.

Sue is thought to be a Catahoula mix and Greta is a Boxer mix.  While we would place each dog separately, we would LOVE to place them together since they really compliment each other and to be honest, they just simply love each other.

The home that would suit them best would be an adult home with a fenced yard so they can run and play (yes, Sue loves to run and play).  What a great pair and it would truly be a wonderful thing to give both of these girls a great home!
animal.name: Greta and Sue (a wonderful pair: 2-3 yrs old)

animal.description:
Angus (formerly ‘Troubles’) originally found himself at Stanislaus County Animal Shelter in January, 2019. He was healthy and in good shape, and luckily he was also microchipped, so he was reunited with his owners. Six months later, Angus once again found himself at the shelter, only this time his owners didn’t come to claim him, and he was in bad shape: his right leg is non-functioning, his spine is out of whack, and he has scars all over his body. Though we’ll never know exactly what happened to Angus in the six months between leaving the shelter and coming back, it definitely wasn’t good.

In spite of everything, Angus is a sweetheart! His body may be broken, but his spirit isn’t; he still trusts people, and isn’t reactive to other dogs in non-stressful settings. He is working through some separation anxiety, which isn’t surprising given what little we know of his history, and will have his medical needs assessed and addressed before going to a forever home. In general, he just wants to be touched, hugged, scratched, and loved. His resilience is astounding!

If you're interested in applying to adopt, please complete an application at www.sacrdr.org/adopt.
To keep up with Angus, check out #SacRDRAngus on Facebook and Instagram @resilientdogrescue

animal.description:
Winston is a two year old Chocolate Lab/German Shorthaired Pointer mix. This special boy does well with other dogs, loves to play fetch, relax in the pool and go on walks.  Winston is a very loving and smart dog, but does need help staying focused and remembering his manners and boundaries. He would do best in a home with an experienced adopter that is comfortable fulfilling the role of a "strong leader" that Winston can trust to steer him in the right direction.   We will not place Winston in a home with kiddos or other dogs.  He can not handle the responsibility of being permitted on a bed or a couch.  Winston is so intelligent that he would love an activity such as dock diving!  

We are looking for adaptors that own a house with a fenced in yard. No town houses. Also a home with no bunnies or cats. 

Mr. Winston is currently being trained while with us.  So we are in search of a local forever family.  Once Winston is adopted, his current trainer will continue to work with him and his new family at no further expense!    

He is housetrained, up-to-date on vaccines and neutered. If you are interested in learning more about Winston, or perhaps would like to schedule a meet-and-greet please contact The Canine Rescue of Central PA at 717-232-1644 or e-mail adopt@crcpa.org.

animal.description:
Dobby is approx 4 year old treeing walker coonhound. He loves to run and play with the other dogs, although he can be selective on who is his friend. He also loves to hang out on the couch and snuggle.

Dobby has been doing more snuggling, less playing, as he was tested heartworm positive when he came in and is currently undergoing treatment. His activities are limited to short walks right now, but he is responding well and will slowly start to add in more activity as we get the clear from his vets! 

Dobby is very food-motivated and LOOVES to work for food. Do you have some treats for him? He could be your new best friend!

11/25/19 Update: Dobby completed his heartworm treatment. The treatment and period of restricted activity was a little hard on him and he had to undergo some behavior modification for resource guarding with Halo K9 behavior. He is currently being slowly re-introduced to his dog friends and caretakers again and is doing well. We will continue to monitor him. 
Dobby is really in need of a forever home where someone can provide the structure, care, and training he needs. Please ask about him and what he needs!

animal.description:
With her smushy, wrinkly face and her wonderful blend of affectionate and independent, Lilly V will bring guaranteed fun and cuteness to every day!

Everyone Lilly V meets describes her as a smart girl who learns fast, including her trainers at the Paws For Life prison program, where she spent several weeks brushing up on her basics. She has a few skills she’s constantly honing out in the world while out on walks, but in addition to those daily bits of training, we also think she’d quite enjoy living with someone who likes to teach her new things. Tricks, fun enrichment, general Cool Stuff Dogs Like--she’s down to try it. Don’t worry, that’s not code for “secret border collie,” but she’s got the brains, so she’d love to go home with someone who wants to use ‘em!

All of Lilly’s fosters have reported back that she does very well in the house--easy in her crate, potty trained, and is the perfect mix of sometimes independent but always ready for a good time. She's the ideal Stay at Home buddy--she'll entertain herself through your Zoom calls but be ready for a play break when you are! 

Lilly V would prefer to be the only dog at home, but could potentially live with a confident cat with a slow introduction.

Check out more from Lilly V on her Instagram at @illy__lilly (https://www.instagram.com/illy__lilly/)

About 3 years old and 55 pounds, Lilly V is crate-trained, house-trained, micro-chipped, up to date on routine vaccinations and knows her basic commands.

animal.description:
When Elvis sang "You 'Aint Nothing But A Hound Dog", he very well may have been singing abou our sweet Stella!    Stella is a 60 pound, approx. 4 year old Coonhound/Treeing Walker/Beagle Mix.   In typical coonhound style, she usually has her nose to the ground.  She is super sweet, calm, and relaxed. She loves her humans and enjoys snuggling.  She loves to run & play with her foster siblings and her humans. She loves attention and has the sweetest disposition. She wants more than anything else to have her very own family to love and adore her.

Like many rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. We require all our dogs over 1 years old  attend 1 obedience class (class is a 6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. animal.description:
Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Holly is a cute, affectionate, sweet and bouncy young dog. She loves people, but should only be living with adults. She is very dog aggressive(including all animals), so definitely should be the only pet in the house. Her new owner(s) would ideally be experienced with the bully breed dogs.

She is very active and will need an owner(s) who can give her enough exercise to wear her out ! She needs a solid, securely fenced yard with a 6-7 ft privacy fence, as she can leap at least 5 ft. She is about 3 yrs old and 35 lbs, a great snuggle size; she's also good on a leash. She's been fully vetted, including spay, vaccines and deworming. She's very playful and loves her toys including old buckets, balls, kongs, antlers, beef bones and anything that can be thrown. Please contact Dee at K9rescueva@gmail.com with any questions, and to meet this sweet girl.

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

animal.description:
Needs: •	Active Adult Home • Solo Dog • Fenced Yard.

Awesome Augie is an extremely intelligent, active and loyal 2 year old, 40 lb Australian Cattle Dog mix who thrives on learning. With the classic smarts and high trainability of this great herding breed, he needs focused accomplishments to occupy his mind. Augie is on a great path in his dog savvy foster home where he is learning agility skills, getting consistent mental and physical stimulation and lots of time with his people. He is seeking a forever home who will continue that journey.

Once Augie has connected with his person, he is deeply affectionate, and enjoys major snuggles at the end of a busy day. Augie loves to explore, and is happy to hop in the car and go on adventures; he makes a great sidekick! 

Our trainer feels this clever boy is a great agility or rally dog prospect. He enjoys walks and hikes, but most of all he likes to use his brain to learn new things. Because of his herding dog heritage, he would do best in a home without children. Augie can be selective with his dog friends so needs to be a solo dog in his forever home, and he finds dog parks too stressful so needs other forms of exercise. 

Augie is house trained, crate trained, excellent on leash, and ready to find an experienced forever home who will enjoy going on Augie doggie adventures with him!


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here:(https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.  All fields on the application must be completed in order for our volunteers to process it (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/) 

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care, so please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested prior to submitting.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health and safety of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering,  and microchipping before transporting our dogs. Then, we provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you. We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources, so if you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Papi
Everyone remembers “Mary Had a Little Lamb” and the part that goes, “Everywhere that Mary went, the lamb was sure to go” Well, I’m that little lamb. Actually, I’m a Dachshund/Chihuahua mix whose favorite spot is with you – on your lap, walking beside you, or having a snooze. It’s where I feel safe. When I’m left alone, I panic. I fear I’ll never see you again because it’s happened before. I’d be best in a home where somebody I know will be with me when you have to leave. Despite my anxiety “issues,” I’m affectionate and bond easily. Would you be my new Mary?
Arrived 7/18/19  Adopted 7/28/19  Arrived 9/9/19

animal.description: Duke is a handsome adult male Catahoula mix with stock dog instincts typical of his breed, also known to be very affectionate with their family! Looking at his athletic body profile we wonder if he might have some Greyhound or Whippet in him, with those long legs and delicate head.  Sadly his family decided to surrender him for adoption due to personal difficulties.  They advise that Duke might not be the best choice for a home with very small children, as he does his best to herd them together and keep 'em corraled!  Though he gets along fine with other dogs Duke does love to chase cats, so your feline friends would definitely not welcome him into the family.   Duke will do best with regular exercise and would make a wonderful walking or jogging companion.  His adoption fee of $95 includes completed neuter surgery and up to date vaccinations, worming, flea control and heartworm prevention. There's also a separate one-time charge of $10.99 for his lifetime, transferable microchip registration with HomeAgain.  If your "grand duchy" could use a new Duke, please GO TO WWW.SPCAOFMC.COM and click on the green arrow icon near the top of the page to fill out an online adoption application.  Thanks for thinking rescue!

animal.description:
Meet Sargent
If this story doesn’t break your heart, we don’t know what will. Sargent’s owner is a soldier . He’s been deployed overseas and has to leave behind his beautiful dog Sargent. With no one to take Sargent in, Sargent was surrendered on July 12, 2019. We thank his owner for his service. We know heading off to war and leaving your best buddy behind is absolutely heartbreaking. We promised we’d to do whatever we could to find Sargent his forever loving home, but after 18 months this gorgeous boy is still waiting.
Sargent is an awesome dog. He was 18 months old when he arrived but now he's almost 3.  He certainly doesn't deserve to spend his life in a shelter. He’s thought to be a Boxer/Australian Shepherd mix. Sargent is a handsome boy with a tan and white coat and one brown and one partial blue eye. His ears are expressive and he looks at you as if he knows what you’re saying. Sargent is on the bigger side weighing 72 pounds. Sargent is mostly house-broken but could use some consistent training to make him just about perfect. He’s smart and knows some commands like sit and shake. Sargent has a lot of energy and will enjoy being part of an active family that’s able to keep his body and mind going. He’s game for most anything. Sargent has a high prey drive. Hedoes not seem to like other dogs and especially doesn’t like cats and will need to be in a home without them.  Sargent fears stressful situations and that’s exactly what he’s in. We hope his stay with us will be short, but that depends on us sharing his story far and wide and finding his home. Please help us pass along his story!
Sargent wasn’t expecting the turn that his life took and we hope he remains as strong as his owner. So far he’s hanging in there, but we know it’s not easy on him. If you’re looking for a wonderful companion dog to welcome into your family, come meet Sargent. You’ll not only be helping Sargent, but also a solder serving our country.
Sargent is microchipped, neutered, and current on vaccinations.
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee. If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog- adoption-application
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted. If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can.an.
